WEBVTT

0
00:00:00.009 --> 00:00:01.210
Introduction to heal.

1
00:00:02.250 --> 00:00:04.469
A trauma informed therapeutic care model.

2
00:00:05.429 --> 00:00:08.630
Children who enter residential or supported accommodation services

3
00:00:08.859 --> 00:00:10.590
often carry the weight of trauma,

4
00:00:10.850 --> 00:00:12.149
disrupted attachments,

5
00:00:12.550 --> 00:00:14.130
developmental vulnerabilities,

6
00:00:14.350 --> 00:00:16.819
and emotional wounds that are not immediately visible.

7
00:00:17.149 --> 00:00:17.549
Traditionally,

8
00:00:17.709 --> 00:00:19.899
behaviour has often been managed through rules,

9
00:00:20.110 --> 00:00:20.709
sanctions,

10
00:00:20.790 --> 00:00:22.299
rewards and consequences

11
00:00:22.549 --> 00:00:23.930
with a focus on stopping

12
00:00:24.069 --> 00:00:25.110
or correcting

13
00:00:25.389 --> 00:00:26.290
what is seen as

14
00:00:26.420 --> 00:00:27.770
challenging behaviour.

15
00:00:28.219 --> 00:00:29.020
For example,

16
00:00:29.270 --> 00:00:32.310
a child who becomes angry or aggressive might lose privileges,

17
00:00:32.549 --> 00:00:33.590
be given a sanction.

18
00:00:33.939 --> 00:00:35.599
Or be removed from an activity

19
00:00:35.979 --> 00:00:38.619
in the hope that this will prevent the behaviour from happening again.

20
00:00:39.259 --> 00:00:39.270
Because

21
00:00:39.580 --> 00:00:40.130
of that,

22
00:00:40.340 --> 00:00:44.200
traditional behaviour management approaches that lean heavily on consequences,

23
00:00:44.580 --> 00:00:46.080
compliance or control

24
00:00:46.229 --> 00:00:47.380
can miss the real issue.

25
00:00:48.389 --> 00:00:50.349
They may reduce behaviour in the short term,

26
00:00:50.669 --> 00:00:52.860
but they rarely reach the underlying distress,

27
00:00:53.229 --> 00:00:53.529
fear,

28
00:00:53.869 --> 00:00:55.770
or unmet need that is driving it.

29
00:00:56.069 --> 00:00:58.330
And they can sometimes reinforce the child's belief

30
00:00:58.509 --> 00:01:00.250
that adults are there to manage them

31
00:01:00.470 --> 00:01:02.229
rather than understand and help them.

32
00:01:03.009 --> 00:01:07.029
The HAL framework has been developed to provide adults with a trauma-informed,

33
00:01:07.209 --> 00:01:08.110
relational,

34
00:01:08.290 --> 00:01:09.589
and therapeutic way

35
00:01:09.769 --> 00:01:11.709
of understanding and supporting children

36
00:01:11.970 --> 00:01:14.989
whose early experiences have shaped their emotional world.

37
00:01:15.410 --> 00:01:17.230
HAL shifts the focus away from

38
00:01:17.449 --> 00:01:18.849
what is this child doing

39
00:01:19.089 --> 00:01:20.870
toward the more important question,

40
00:01:21.209 --> 00:01:22.629
what does this child live through

41
00:01:22.769 --> 00:01:24.050
and what do they need to heal?

42
00:01:24.739 --> 00:01:27.019
By reframing behaviour as communication,

43
00:01:27.459 --> 00:01:30.760
Heel empowers caregivers to become agents of emotional recovery

44
00:01:31.019 --> 00:01:32.699
rather than enforcers of discipline.